snippet.textDisplay:
Having had to clean and repair keyboards a few times, I don't see any way that will work, and even if it did, and it survived, water still inside will slowly corrode the contacts.
It would have been nice if they separated the case to verify that it was dry(I think I can guarantee it wasn't, unless they put them under a heat lamp or baked them at a really low temp) and clean.
For membrane keyboards, once the water gets between the layers, I don't see it coming out very easy at all without disassembly.
Also, I like to use deoxit on all contacts, which you cannot do without disassembly.

Really quick and efficient: take off the keys (take a pic!) drench everything with wd40, let sit for a few minutes, clean with a medium-soft brush, reapply wd40 as needed, rinse generously and wipe with alcohol, put the keys back. Less than 20min. Looks brand new! It works for the worst nicotine and dust incrusted hardware...even gpu, motherboards, etc. you name it.
You can alternatively speed up drying water damage by putting a thin towel on a radiator and the piece of equipment on it overnight.

snippet.textDisplay: The secret to wet washing any electronics is drying. I've worked in electro-mechanical disaster restoration for over 20 years and have stripped and washed literally thousands of PC's (as well as far more complex cabinets and research equipment) as long as the items are dried thoroughly then they'll generally be fine (using de-ionised water and rinsing properly helps as well). To dry them relatively quickly stick the parts in the oven for 12 hours @ 50C. Be warned though, don't go over 50C or you'll melt the plastic components.

snippet.textDisplay: You're supposed to take the keyboard apart before putting it in the dishwasher (i.e. separating the top and bottom half and the electronic board). You lose the warranty anyway. In our student union office from time to time we gathered all keyboards, took them apart, put the key caps in the cutlery box, the bottom and top cover in the dish rack, the electronic board and cord stayed out(!). Lowest temperature, with soap. Everything is spotless clean. Drying took some hours, not days, because there is not closed space where water could get trapped.

£300 worth of corsair k70's - cos $5 second hand membrane kbd's just wouldn't give the same results....? TROLLS !
ps quickest way to clean kbd's - remove keycaps (soak them in a light bleach solution then set aside into individual piles for each row (you'll be thankful when it comes to putting the keys back cos it's ALWAYS the last key you turn over that's the one you were looking for! it's the rules).
Now brush keyless board with a stiff paint brush or similar semi stiff bristle brush to remove initial gunk, then wipe between keys with anti-bacterial hand wipe/babies wipes, then qtips for tough spots with "something that evaporates quickly yet cleans" (alcohol?) lastly then paper towels... reassemble and forget it for another 5 years i mean 1 year ....

snippet.textDisplay:
Before finishing the video the best way is clearly:
1. Remove all key caps
2. Wipe with a soft cloth (wet if preferred)
3. Blow out all switches with compressed air/shake keyboard (If wet method is used in step 2 use a dry cloth to clean all key caps)
4. Replace all key caps after 4-6 hours (if using non-water method time can be reduced to 2-4 hours)
5. Keyboard is as good as new, repeat as soon as desirable. For best results 6 months to 1 years per clean is recommended as well as using wet clean for key caps with extended drying time

snippet.textDisplay:
In my experience, dishwashers kinda suck. I'd probably rather soak them in soap water, and then pressure rinse with the sink's spray nozzle (after removing keys). Particularly and especially if I didn't have a brand new dishwasher.

If I was in a hurry for it to dry, I'd stick it next to a running de-humidifier in a small room closet, maybe even do an isopropyl alcohol bath after the pressure rinse if it was my only keyboard, then the closet with the de-humidifier.

snippet.textDisplay: In the late '70s I worked for a company that made array processors.  An array processor is a specialized high speed computer attached to a minicomputer that does high precision linear programming on large arrays. Examples: seismic data, CT data, MRI data, signal processing, sonar. The company was still small, and money was tight. Circuit boards were hand-soldered. They were cleaned in an old dishwasher that someone had brought in, before heading to final assembly. One Friday evening, a bunch of memory boards were put in the dishwasher for cleaning. The control on the dishwasher failed, and was still running on Monday morning. Over a dozen $40k boards were delaminated. Most of the chips were salvaged, but it was still very expensive. The shipping schedule literally went down the drain.
